    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1908-03-31T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1908-03-31T00:00:00-05:00" n="532"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d532">
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Chargé <persName type="from">Carter</persName> to the <gloss
                            type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">American Embassy</hi>,<lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">London</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1908-03-31">
                            <hi rend="italic">March 31, 1908</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>I am sending by fast steamer to-day a copy of Sir Edward Greg’s instruction to
                    British minister at Brussels, dated 27th instant,<note n="1" xml:id="d532fn1"
                        >See British print “Africa,” No. 3, 1905, cd. 4135.</note> in which he
                    explains British Government’s view of the treaty obligations of the Kongo Free
                    State; also what, in their opinion, is required to bring the administration of
                    that State into harmony with these obligations.</p>
                <p>British minister at Brussels is directed to communicate this instruction to
                    Belgian minister for foreign affairs, after consultation with Wilson.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Carter.</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
